T1  - Alcohol: Demand and taxation under monopoly and oligopoly in South India in the 1970s
AU  - Musgrave, Simon
AU  - Stern, Nicholas
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
SP  - 1
EP  - 41
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/02/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(88)90012-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387888900120
AB  - Our first objective, is the investigation of the determinants of recorded demand for alcohol, and particularly arrack, in terms of price and income elasticities, taxation and household characteristics. Second, we develop an analysis of some simple theoretical aspects of the revenue system in Karnataka, involving the auction of the monopoly right to sell legally in a district. This leads to an examination of the theory of taxation in spatial and non-spatial oligopoly. Third, we combine these different elements to comment on policy in Karnataka. We hope to demonstrate some techniques and provide insights which can be productively used for a range of important problems in taxation and demand estimation for developing countries.
